FINAL PROJECT

Guiding Question

Question

What is the relationship between languages spoken in a country to the respective social and economic development of the country in 2014?

Why this Topic

Growing up both in India and America as a student, I grew up speakign 4 languages and was in an environment where some of my peers spoke upwards of 6-10 langueges due to the language diversity within India. The concepts of language had always intrigued me growing up, it was a form of social currency.

On coming to Penn State and back to America after 10 years I came to relazie that most American barely speak more than 2 languages. While being a Major industiral hub, and economic leader i wondered how does the Languages spoken in a country affect its enconomy and society.

Hence I’ve chosen this topic!

  read_html() %>%
  html_nodes(css = "table") %>%
  html_table(fill = TRUE)

Data Wrangling for Languages

The renaming of varaibles in the Languages DataFrame

# CODE
names(Languages)[c(2,3,4,5,6,7,8,9)] <- c("country", "count_lang","immigrant","total","percent","t", "mean", "median")

Since we will only need to be using the number of languages per country information from the Languages DataFrame, we transform the database to accomodate our requirments

# CODE
Languages <-
  Languages %>%
  filter(row_number() > 1) %>%
  select(country,count_lang) %>%
  mutate(count_lang = as.numeric(count_lang))

Joining both Datasets

Creation of a Hypothesis DataFrame that we will use for analysis for the rest of the project by joining the Languages and Country Data DataFrame with the respective identifiers we wish to analyze (eg. GDP growth, netUsers etc.)

# CODE
Hypo <-
  Languages %>%
  left_join(CountryData %>% select(country,GDPgrowth, obesity,,netUsers,pop,growth), by = c("country" = "country"))

Hypo

Relationship between Languages spoken and GDP Growth

Using Graphics to show some informative plots and summary statistics to see if there is a relationship between languages spoken in country and growth of countries GDP

# CODE
# Scatterplot Graph
Hypo %>%
  mutate(country = reorder(country, count_lang)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=GDPgrowth, y= count_lang)) + stat_smooth() + geom_point() +
  ggtitle("Relationship between Languages spoken and GDP Growth") +
  labs(y = "Number of Langues Spoken")

Seing the confidence interval being large we can see there is not much of a relationship between the two varaibles

Relationship between Languages spoken and Obesity rate

Using Graphics to show some informative plots and summary statistics to see if there is a relationship between languages spoken in country and obesity of country

# CODE
# Density Graph
Hypo %>%
  mutate(country = reorder(country, count_lang)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=obesity)) + geom_density(stat = "density",
  position = "identity",adjust = 0.4) +
  ggtitle("Relationship between Languages spoken and Obesity rate")

We can see that the density for countries where higher languages are spoken,the obesetiy count is lower for that country

Relationship between Languages spoken and Internet Users

Using Graphics to show some informative plots and summary statistics to see if there is a relationship between languages spoken in country and internet users of country

# CODE
# Scatterplot Graph
Hypo %>%
  mutate(country = reorder(country, count_lang)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=country, y= netUsers)) +
  stat_smooth(aes(),method='loess') +
  geom_point() +
  scale_y_log10() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_blank()) +
  ggtitle("Relationship between Languages spoken and Internet Users")

# CODE
# Boxplot Graph
Hypo %>%
  mutate(country = reorder(country, count_lang)) %>%
  mutate(netGroup = mosaic::ntiles(netUsers, n = 4, format = "interval")) %>%
  drop_na(netGroup) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=count_lang, y=netGroup)) +
  geom_boxplot() + scale_x_log10() +
  ggtitle("Boxplot Relationship between Languages spoken\nand Internet Users") +
  labs(x = "Number of Languages Spoken" )

Seing this graphic we can see that countries with more languages spoken have more internet

Relationship between Languages spoken and Population of the Country

Using Graphics to show some informative plots and summary statistics to see if there is a relationship between languages spoken in country and Population of the country

# CODE
# Scatterplot Graph
Hypo %>%
  select(country, count_lang,pop) %>%
  mutate(country = reorder(country, count_lang)) %>%
  mutate(the_rank = rank(-pop)) %>% # creating a variable to rank the poplations
  ggplot(aes(x = the_rank, y= count_lang)) + geom_point() + stat_smooth() +
  ggtitle("Relationship between Languages spoken\nand Population of the Country") +
  labs(x = "<~ Higher (Ranking: Population of Country) Lower ~>") +
  labs(y = "Number of Langues Spoken")

Seeing from this graph the higher the population corrosponds to higher lannguages counts. There is a strong relarionship as the confidence inteval is also narrow!

Now what would this look like for countires where thier population increases or decreases per yer?

Relationship between Languages spoken and Population in relation to Poupulation Growth of the Country

Using Graphics to show some informative plots and summary statistics to see if there is a relationship between languages spoken in country and Population growth of the country


Hypo %>%
  select(country, count_lang,pop, growth) %>%
  mutate(the_rank = rank(-pop)) %>%
  mutate(country = reorder(country, count_lang)) %>%
  mutate( growth = growth <0) %>% # Check for all Psitive Growth countries
  drop_na(growth) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = the_rank, y= count_lang))+
  geom_point() + stat_smooth(method = lm) +
  facet_wrap(~growth)+
  ggtitle("Relationship between Languages spoken and Population\nin relation to the Poupulation Growth of the Country") +
  labs(x = "<~ Higher (Ranking: Population of Country) Lower ~>") +
  labs(y = "Number of Langues Spoken")

Seeing from this graph we can say that for countries with positve growth of population there is a minimum relationship between the Languages spoken and Population in country, as the number of langues spoken and the poplation slop remains constant throughout whereas for coutnries with negative growth the is a stronger realtionship between these two identifiers

Conclusion

We can see that through the above analysis that:

  1. For GDP Growth there is no relationship
  2. For Obesity Rate there is a relationship and it is negative
  3. For Internet Users there is a relationship and it is positve
  4. For Poulation there is a relationship and is it positve
  5. For Population Growth the is no relationship

Therefore the Percentage of Indentifiers with a Relationship

\(P = {\frac{3}{5}*100}= 60\%\)

Therefore the Percentage of Indentifiers with no a Relationship

\(P = {\frac{2}{5}*100}= 40\%\)

THerefore we can infer that there is on a whole with 76 variables in Country Date there is Mild Relationship with Number of Languages spoken in that respective Country.
